ty of religion is on the rise, leading to questions about religious authority: Where does it come from? How is it established? What might be changing it? The contributors to The Media and Religious Authority examine the ways in which new centers of power and influence are emerging as religions seek to "brand" themselves in the media age. Putting their in-depth, incisive studies of particular instances of media production and reception in Asia, Africa, Latin America, and North America into conversation with one another, the volume explores how evolving mediations of religion in various places affect the prospects, aspirations, and durability of religious authority across the globe.An insightful combination of theoretical groundwork and individual case studies, The Media and Religious Authority invites us to rethink the relationships among the media, religion, and culture.The contributors are Karina Kosicki Bellotti, Alexandra Boutros, Pauline Hope Cheong, Peter Horsfield, Christine Hoff Kraemer, Joonseong Lee, Alf Linderman, Bahíyyah Maroon, Montré Aza Missouri, and Emily Zeamer, with an afterword by Lynn Schofield Clark.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAuthorityxReligious aspects. 0aMass mediaxReligious aspects. 7aRELIGION / Leadership.2bisacsh1 aBoutros, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCheong, Pauline Hope, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoff Kraemer, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoover, Steward M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoover, Stewart M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoover, Stewart M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHorsfield, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https:/